      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my physics midterm and im kinda stuck on entanglement. can u give me a quick summary of what quantum entanglement actually is? also how is it different from just regular classical correlation? thx",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a fascinating concept where two or more particles become linked in such a way that they share the same fate, no matter how far apart they are.  If you measure a property of one entangled particle, you instantly know the corresponding property of the other, even if it's across the galaxy.  The difference from classical correlation is the *instantaneity* and the *non-local* nature of this connection, which is what makes it so weird and powerful. It's like having two perfectly matched, yet utterly unpredictable, magic coins that always land opposite each other, even if one is in your pocket and the other is with a distant cousin.",
      "source": "target",
