    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "the coin thing makes sense but it still feels a bit hand-wavy. a lot of books call it \"spooky action at a distance.\" why did einstein call it that? what's the actual logic behind why it's considered so spooky or weird compared to just normal physics?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Einstein called it \"spooky action at a distance\" because it seemed to violate the principle of locality, which is a cornerstone of classical physics. Locality essentially means that an object can only be influenced by its immediate surroundings, and no influence can travel faster than the speed of light. The entanglement connection, however, appears to be instantaneous—the measurement on one particle *instantly* dictates the state of the other, regardless of the distance separating them. It's spooky because it suggests a connection that seems to bypass the cosmic speed limit, which is something our everyday, predictable world doesn't allow.",
      "source": "target",
